Fit a model to predict accuracy following each cue type in each experiment condition. flicker and interval were varied between-subjects. cue type was varied within-subjects. Trials were evenly distributed between frame cues, sound cues, and no cue baseline trials. To estimate the effect of each cue (frame, sound) relative to baseline performance, two contrast variables were created. These contrast variables (frame_v_nocue and sound_v_nocue) are interpreted as the independent cueing effects of frames and sounds.

We are testing the hypothesis that the cueing effects are differentially affected by the flicker and interval manipulations. In particular, we expect the frame_v_nocue cueing effect to be more affected by the flicker manipulation than the sound_v_nocue cueing effect.

The contention is that it is only in a relatively small window of conditions that visual cues “outperform” so-called endogenous cues. For a majority of the visual tasks in our everyday lives, we are constantly confronted by irrelevant information and distractions. When there are distractions, such as a flickering visual mask, exogenous cues are not as effective for achieving heightened visual awareness.

contrast_cols <- c("frame_v_nocue", "sound_v_nocue")
cueing[,contrast_cols] <- create_cue_type_treatment_contrasts(cueing$cue_type)
cueing$flicker_c <- center_flicker(cueing$flicker)
cueing$interval_c <- center_interval(cueing$interval)

accuracy_mod <- glmer(is_correct ~ (frame_v_nocue + sound_v_nocue) * (flicker_c + interval_c) + 
                        (frame_v_nocue + sound_v_nocue || subj_id),
                      family = "binomial", data = cueing)
summary(accuracy_mod)

between_subj_conditions <- expand.grid(
    flicker = c("on", "off"),
    interval = c(0.75, 0.10)
  ) %>% filter(!(flicker == "off" & interval == 0.10))  # don't get preds for missing exp
between_subj_conditions$exp <- row.names(between_subj_conditions)
between_subj_conditions
##   flicker interval exp
## 1      on     0.75   1
## 2     off     0.75   2
## 3      on     0.10   3
library(broom)
library(purrr)

cueing_effects_in_accuracies <- between_subj_conditions %>% 
  # for each experiment
  split(.$exp) %>%
  
  # fit a model to predict the cueing effects
  map(~ glmer(is_correct ~ frame_v_nocue + sound_v_nocue + (frame_v_nocue + sound_v_nocue || subj_id),
              data = filter(cueing, flicker == .$flicker, interval == .$interval),
              family = "binomial")
  ) %>%
  
  # extract the parameter estimates from the model
  map(tidy, effects = "fixed") %>%
  map(filter, term %in% c("frame_v_nocue", "sound_v_nocue")) %>%
  
  # relabel the between subject conditions
  rbind_all(.) %>%
  mutate(
    flicker = rep(between_subj_conditions$flicker, each = 2),
    interval = rep(between_subj_conditions$interval, each = 2)
  )

The experiments reported here do not establish why exogenous and endogenous cues differ in this way, a question to be addressed in future work. They do, however, motivate that work.

Traditionally, the difference between exogenous and endogenous cues has been attributed to time. Exogenous cues are faster acting than endogenous cues. There is also an element of volition: exogenous cues are automatic, whereas endogenous cues can be discounted.

But an implicit assumption in the literature is that controlling for these other factors, exogenous and endogenous cues can mean roughly the same thing when it comes to cueing a particular spatial location. Under the hood it is the same “spotlight of attention” in both cueing conditions.
